      "content": "Changes made to Gillette Stadium for World Cup. Here's what they are - Yahoo SportsAdvertisementAdvertisementAdvertisementAdvertisementWatch LiveIFL: NAZ Wranglers vs. New Mexico ChupacabrasWatch LiveTRENDINGWorld Cup live updatesU.S. Open live updatesCollege World Series updatesSchwarber, Harper crush MetsReese gets best of Clark againStory byWicked LocalSeth Jacobson, USA TODAY NETWORK - New EnglandTue, Jun 9, 2026·2 min readEveryone knows that the FIFA World Cup is coming to Massachusetts, but fans might not know about the changes being made at Gillette Stadium for the occasion.And there are quite a few of them.One big change at Gillette Stadium for the World Cup included the removal of the usual artificial turf on the field and replacing it with natural grass, as FIFA mandates in its rulebook.AdvertisementAdvertisementAdvertisementRyan Bjorn, Gillette Stadium's field superintendent, explained to Wicked Local media partner WCVB Channel 5 that the entire replacement process, from removing the artificial turf to laying the last sod, took about six weeks.\"Luckily, here at the stadium, it was built as a natural grass field originally. We have a full hydronic heating system underneath, so essentially it’s a 2-acre heated floor with a radiant heating system,\" Bjorn told WCVB in a report. \"We can control soil temperature really well. We have what is called a sub-air system, which is essentially a giant vacuum that we can actually pull water down through the profile. That helps manage moisture. We also have grow lights that we can deploy onto the field to help, essentially, mimic natural sunlight.\"Here are some of the other changes happening at Gillette Stadium because of the World Cup.Gillette Stadium, which is decked out in FIFA World Cup gear will be known as Boston Stadium throughout the tournament, on Tuesday, June 2, 2026.What are some changes being made at Gillette Stadium for the World Cup matches?The following changes are according to reports on YouTube, the Patriot Ledger, USA Today and the Field Level Media website:AdvertisementAdvertisementAdvertisementGillette Stadium in Foxborough, MA is being rebranded as \"Boston Stadium.\"All Gillette branding and corporate sponsor logos that violate FIFA rules have been covered with sheets and tarps.Refillable, hard-sided plastic water bottles have now been banned by FIFA from all stadiums hosting World Cup matches because of safety concerns. Fans can, however, bring in one soft, plastic, 20-ounce water bottle, according to FIFA's Instagram.A layered \"fortress\" security setup will include heavy barricades, extra fencing and strict ID and ticket checks.The Patriots Pro Shop at Gillette Stadium was temporarily relocated to the South Retail marketplace at Patriot Place for the duration of the World Cup.Tailgating is permitted but highly limited; you must have a valid match ticket to tailgate.Public parking at the stadium has been drastically reduced for the World Cup.There will be no MBTA subway or bus service to the stadium aside from the Boston Stadium Train services. Round-trip service costs $80.Crowd control gates and portable toilets are set up in the parking lot of Gillette Stadium, which will be call Boston Stadium by FIFA, ahead of the month of 2026 World Cup games. Gillette Stadium's set up as seen on Tuesday, June 2, 2026.What World Cup games are being played at Gillette Stadium?They include:June 13, 2026 (9 p.m. ET): Haiti vs. ScotlandJune 16, 2026 (6 p.m. ET): Iraq vs. NorwayJune 19, 2026 (3 p.m. ET): Scotland vs. MoroccoJune 23, 2026 (4 p.m. ET): England vs. GhanaJune 26, 2026 (3 p.m. ET): Norway vs. FranceJune 29, 2026 (4:30 p.m. ET): Round of 32 (Group E Winner vs. Group A/B/C/D/F Third Place)July 9, 2026 (4 p.m. ET): QuarterfinalThis article originally appeared on wickedlocal.com: What changes were made at Gillette Stadium for World Cup? What to knowAbout Our AdsAdvertisementAdvertisementAdvertisement",
